
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    `gdbtui` yek ravash grafiki (graphical) baraye estefade az `gdb` (GNU Debugger) ast.  Ba estefade az `gdbtui`, shoma mitoonid code-e khod ra ba asani bebinid, khat be khat ejra konid va moteghayyer-ha (variables) ra barresi konid dar yek mahite terminal.  In barname komak mikonad debug kardan barname-ha asantar shavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `gdbtui <name_barname>`  --> 🚀 Ejra kardan `gdbtui` ba yek barname moshakhas.
    🔹 `gdbtui -help` --> ❓ Namayesh rahnamaye `gdbtui`.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gdbtui myprogram

    🔹 Ejra kardan `gdbtui` baraye barname-ye "myprogram".

    $ gdbtui

    🔹 Ejra kardan `gdbtui` bedune barname avaliye (mitavanid file ra dar dakhel `gdb` baz konid).

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ gdbtui a.out
    🔹 In dastoor barname-ye `a.out` ra dar `gdbtui` baz mikonad, va shoma mitoonid az terminal-e khod barname-e khod ra debug konid ba estefade az interface-e grafiki.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    `gdbtui` provides a terminal user interface (TUI) for the GNU Debugger (`gdb`).  It allows you to debug programs with a visual representation of the source code, registers, and other debugging information directly within your terminal.  This makes debugging more intuitive and efficient.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `gdbtui <program_name>` --> 🚀 Run `gdbtui` with a specified program.
    🔹 `gdbtui -help` --> ❓ Display the `gdbtui` help message.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gdbtui myprogram

    🔹 Run `gdbtui` to debug the program "myprogram".

    $ gdbtui

    🔹 Run `gdbtui` without a program initially (you can open the file within `gdb`).

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ gdbtui a.out
    🔹 This command opens the program `a.out` in `gdbtui`, allowing you to debug your code from the terminal using the graphical interface.
